In pentagon $MATHS$, one of the interior angles ($\angle A$) is supplementary to another angle ($\angle S$), and the rest of the interior angles are all congruent. 

We know that the sum of all the interior angles in a pentagon is $540^{\circ}$. Furthermore, since $\angle A$ and $\angle S$ are supplementary, we can state: 
\begin{align*}
\angle A + \angle S
&= 180^{\circ}\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad \angle A = 180^{\circ}-\angle S
\end{align*}

Since the rest of the angles in the pentagon are congruent, and the measure of $\angle A$ has the relation 
$$\angle A\approx \dfrac{1}{3}(\angle A+\angle S+\angle T+\angle H+\angle M)$$
we can denote all the interior angles in the pentagon as $x$. Since the sum of all the inside angles is $540^{\circ}$, and $\angle A+\angle S = 180^{\circ}$, we can state:
$$5x = 540^{\circ}+180^{\circ}$$

Solving this gives us, 
$$x = 144^{\circ}$$

So, we see that the correct measure of $\angle H$ (with all the congruent ones are) is $144^{\circ}$.

